<doc id="12257" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=12257" title="Gamma">
Gamma

The Greek letter Gamma ' was derived from the Phoenician letter Gimel . Letters that arose from the Greek gamma include the Latin (or latinized) gamma ', the Roman C and G, and the Cyrillic letters Г and Ґ.
In general use, Greek gamma is found throughout the many diverse branches of science, engineering, and mathematics, as well as in phonetic transcription.
Uses.
Greek.
Gamma (uppercase ', lowercase '; "Gámma") is the third letter of the Greek alphabet. In the system of Greek numerals it has a value of 3. In Ancient Greek, gamma represented a voiced velar stop . In Modern Greek, it represents a voiced fricative. It is realized either as a palatal (before a front vowel, /e, i/), or as a velar (in all other environments). Both in Ancient and in Modern Greek, before other velars (κ, χ, ξ "k, kh, ks"), gamma represents a velar nasal . A double gamma γγ represents the sequence (phonetically varying ) or .
Phonetic transcription.
Lowercase Greek gamma is used in the Americanist phonetic notation and Uralic Phonetic Alphabet to indicate voiced consonants.
Mathematics and science.
Lower case.
The lower-case letter formula_1 is used as a symbol for:
Upper case.
The upper-case letter formula_3 is used as a symbol for:
Technical notes.
HTML.
The HTML entities for uppercase and lowercase gamma are codice_1 and codice_2.
These characters are used only as mathematical symbols. Stylized Greek text should be encoded using the normal Greek letters, with markup and formatting to indicate text style.

